\begin{abstract}
  Printing annotated font tables in the layout following the Unicode
  standard documentation is discussed. Existing tools are presented and
  desirable but missing features are proposed.
\end{abstract}

\section{Unicode charts}
\label{sec:unicode-charts}

In this article, we will discuss the primary Unicode
charts;\footnote{\tbsurl{unicode.org/charts}} the secondary charts
describing the variation sequences, in particular those belonging to
Ideographic Variation Database, are outside the scope of our interest.

All the charts are produced with the Unibook formatting
software,\footnote{\tbsurl{unicode.org/unibook}} supplied by
\acro{ASMUS}, Inc.\ (a company owned by Asmus Freytag, Technical Vice
President of the Unicode Consortium from 1991 to 2007). A version of
Unibook is available free of charge (but with a rather complicated
license); it is used to prepare proposals of new characters, as well as
the full standard. The program runs on several versions of \acro{MS}
Windows. The fonts used to print the characters themselves in the charts
come from many sources and are not, in general, free in any
sense.\footnote{\tbsurl{unicode.org/charts/fonts.html}}

The charts proper are followed by various annotations. The source of
annotations, at least in principle, is the
\fname{NamesList.txt}\footnote{\tbsurl{unicode.org/Public/UNIDATA/NamesList.txt}}
file belonging to the Unicode Character Database. Its header states:
\textit{This file is semi-automatically derived from UnicodeData.txt
  and a set of manually created annotations using a script to select
  or suppress information from the data file.} The documentation of
the format of the file is
provided.\footnote{\tbsurl{unicode.org/Public/UCD/latest/ucd/NamesList.html}}
However, there are systematic discrepancies between the content of the
file and the charts, so somewhere in the workflow additional
processing is performed.

As of the standard version 15.0, there are the following annotations
used (examples are given later):

\begin{itemize}
\item Lines starting with • (\ucode{2022} \uname{BULLET}) are just comment lines.
\item Lines starting with = (\ucode{003D} \uname{EQUALS SIGN}) are
  alias lines.
\item Lines starting with ※ (\ucode{203B} \uname{REFERENCE MARK}) are
  formal alias lines.\footnote{Formal aliases are used for control
    characters, which have no glyphs and official names. Another use
    is correcting name mistakes; because of the stability principle,
    erroneous names are not removed from the standard, but the correct
    names are added as a formal alias.}
\item Lines starting with → (\ucode{2192} \uname{RIGHTWARDS ARROW})
  contain cross-references to related characters.
\item Lines starting with ≡ (\ucode{2261} \uname{IDENTICAL TO}) are
  used for precomposed characters and contain the list of characters
  which together compose the character in question.\footnote{Some
    characters `decompose' into another single character, but this is
    another story; the most well-known example is \ucode{212B}
    \uname{ANGSTROM SIGN}, which `decomposes' into \ucode{00C5}
    \uname{LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A WITH RING ABOVE}.}
\item Lines starting with ≈ (\ucode{2248} \uname{ALMOST EQUAL TO})
  are used for so-called compatibility
  characters\footnote{\raggedright See
  \tbsurl{en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicode_compatibility_characters}, for
  example.}
  and show the compatibility decomposition of the character (this
  relation is defined by enumeration).
\item Lines starting with \~{} (\ucode{007E} \uname{TILDE}) describe
  registered variation sequences.
\end{itemize}

The file also contain commands to control printing titles, subtitles,
block headers, various subheaders and notices.


\section{The fntsample tool and its extension}
\label{sec:fntsample-tool-its}

In 2007 Eugeniy Meshcheryakov 
(the original spelling seems to be {\Cyrillic Евгений Мещеряков})
released the first version of the \textsf{fntsample}
program.\footnote{\tbsurl{github.com/eugmes/fntsample}} The
tool was developed for the DejaVu Fonts project.

 \begin{figure}
   \centering
   \includegraphics[width=.99\hsize]{Junicode15p-sample-crop.pdf}
   \caption{\raggedright Output of\newline
\texttt{fntsample -f JunicodeTwoBeta-Regular.ttf \newline
-i 0xf0000- -o sample.pdf}}
   \label{fig:fntsample}
 \end{figure}

 The charts it generates resemble those of the Unicode standard;
 see Fig.~\ref{fig:fntsample}. In particular, they include glyphs for
 the characters which are invisible by definition, such as \VSone\
 (\ucode{FE00} \uname{VARIATION SELECTOR\mbox{-}1}), if the font contains
 them.

 In 2013 a student of mine, Paweł Parafiński, accepted the task to made
 the samples even more similar to the Unicode charts by supplementing
 them with annotations. He solved the problem in two steps. First he
 created a parser for the \fname{NamesList.txt} file which converted
 it into simple \XML. In the second step he extended \textsf{fntsample}
 to print the additional information from the \XML\ file.

 The program is orphaned, but the repositories are still
 available;\footnote {Now at
   \tbsurl{github.com/jsbien/fntsample-with-comments} and
   \tbsurl{github.com/jsbien/ucd_xml_parser}.} in
 particular, this allows reporting the issues. The most annoying problem is
the  inability to break long character names. There was also a problem with
 the parser, which was coded in the now-obsolete Python 2. I managed
 to adapt it to Python 3 (by trial and error, as I am not a
 programmer).

 Unfortunately the parser ignores some elements of the
 \fname{NamesList.txt} file, as at the time of its design
 they seemed not to be needed.
 

\section{Frank Mittelbach's unicodefonttable}
\label{sec:mitt-unic}
Frank Mittelbach's \textsf{unicodefonttable} package is available from
\CTAN\ and the usual distributions; its source repository is
  \tbsurl{github.com/frankmittelbach/fmitex-unicodefonttable}. It
provides a \LaTeX\ style file to include a font table in a document and, an
interactive standalone version to produce a font table as a separate
document.
Tables can be supplemented by block names and user captions;
tables can be limited to selected blocks.

The \textsf{unicodefonttable} package is implemented using the
\textsf{fontspec} package, which is an advantage, as this allows using
all font features which the package supports. The source of the Junicode font manual
\cite{baker22:Junicode}, typeset with \XeLaTeX{}, gives extensive
examples of the usage of font features with the \textsf{fontspec}
package.\tbsurlfootnote{github.com/psb1558/Junicode-font} They are
also discussed in the manual~\cite[p.~13]{baker22:Junicode}:
\begin{quote}
  Many OpenType features produce different outcomes depending on an
  index passed to an application’s layout engine along with the
  feature tag. Different applications have different ways of entering
  this index: consult your application’s documentation. Here, the
  index is recorded in brackets after the feature tag. Users of
  \textsf{fontspec} (with \XeLaTeX{} or \LuaTeX{}) should also be aware that
  \textsf{fontspec} indexes start at zero while OpenType indexes start at
  one. Therefore all index numbers listed in this document must be
  reduced by one for use with fontspec.
\end{quote}
For referencing a specific value of a feature we
follow~\cite{baker22:Junicode}, e.g., \textsf{cv02[1]} means the feature \textsf{cv02}
(character variant number~2) with the index~1; on the other hand
\textsf{ss10} is an example of a feature (stylistic set number 10) which does
not require an index but which is just on or off.

It is worth noting that \textsf{fontspec}, and hence also
\textsf{unicodefonttable}, if used with \LuaLaTeX, allow for the
little known ``raw feature''
\texttt{-invisible},\footnote{\tbsurl{github.com/latex3/luaotfload/issues/63}}
allowing printing glyphs for characters which are invisible in
principle (mentioned earlier; see also, for example, \cite{L2/02-368})
if the font contains them.\footnote{\raggedright I learned this from
  the author; see
  \tbsurl{github.com/FrankMittelbach/fmitex-unicodefonttable/issues/5}.}

Figure \ref{fig:plane15} shows the output of the following:
\begin{verbatim}
\displayfonttable
  [range-start=F0000,range-end=FFFFF,
   nostatistics,noheader,hex-digits=block]
  {JunicodeTwoBeta-Regular.ttf}
\end{verbatim}

