\section{David M. Jones' \acro{STIX} charts}
\label{sec:david-jones-stix}
The charts for the \acro{STIX} fonts (\textit{OpenType Unicode fonts for
  Scientific, Technical, and Mathematical
  texts}\footnote{\tbsurl{https://github.com/stipub} and
  \tbsurl{https://www.stixfonts.org}}) are typeset by David~M. Jones
with \XeLaTeX{} from source generated by a Perl script. The principal
part of the charts has the same layout as the Unicode charts, so this
technique could be used to replace \textsf{fntsample} (the additional
part of the charts describes the OpenType features, which is only
indirectly related to the present paper). Figure~\ref{fig:STIX} shows
the page for the Greek and Coptic block, starting at \ucode{037}. These
charts use some additional conventions, e.g., red (grayscaled for print)
is used for characters not directly supported but synthesized by a
Unicode-aware shaping engine; this is shown with characters \ucode{03D3}
and \ucode{03D4} in the figure; \ucode{0374} is another example of a
character which ``decomposes'' into (is substituted by) another single
character.\footnote{\tbsurl{https://github.com/stipub/stixfonts/issues/248}}

\begin{figure}
\includegraphics[width=\hsize,trim=158 85 158 125,clip]
                {STIXTwoText-Regular9.pdf}
\caption{\raggedright A page from
\texttt{STIXTwoText-Regular.pdf} (headers and footers are omitted).}
\label{fig:STIX}
\end{figure}

At present neither the \XeLaTeX\ source nor the Perl script are
available
publicly.\footnote{\tbsurl{https://github.com/stipub/stixfonts/issues/247}}

\section{Typesetting character annotations}
\label{sec:types-char-adnot}

Although in the Unicode standard the character annotations occur
immediately after the relevant glyph tables, it is not necessary to
follow the standard in this respect. Separately provided annotations
can be even more convenient.

Typesetting individual annotations in a way approximating the Unicode
charts is not difficult. After some research I decided to use
\textsf{xltabular}, which handles multipage tables (unfortunately it
doesn't work in a multicolumn environment).  The examples in
figures~\ref{fig:std}--\ref{fig:variation} are typeset using code
like this (showing just the first line; formatting has been slightly
changed):
