The Unicode conventions can be used easily to describe Private Use
Area characters, e.g., those from Medieval Unicode Font
Initiative\tbsurlfootnote{mufi.info} (other interesting initiatives are
\acro{CONSCRIPT}\footnote{\tbsurl{www.kreativekorp.com/ucsur}} and
\acro{LINCUA}\footnote{\tbsurl{bit.ly/2XVTzRL-LINCUA}}), or from a
specific font.
%\cite{baker22:Junicode}.
Fig.~\ref{fig:pua} shows some examples.

The line format for the registered variation sequences can be easily
adapted to tag variation sequences (see, for example, \cite{JSB22}) and
font specific information, as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:variation}.

The information about the font can be skipped when not needed.

\section{Providing character annotations}
\label{sec:prov-char-adnot}

In addition to the \textsf{ttx} program discussed later, the other tool I know of to list font features in a human-readable form is
\textsf{layout-features.py},\footnote{\tbsurl{github.com/fonttools/fonttools/blob/8ab6af03c89726cf80ca3c4b755ae1bd0038b5da/Snippets/layout-features.py};
see also
\tbsurl{github.com/fonttools/fonttools/discussions/2873}.\raggedright} but
its simple output does not contain the information needed for our
purposes (see Fig.~\ref{fig:layout-features}).


 \begin{figure}
