...
\end{verbatim}
   \caption{\raggedright Some of the output from
\texttt{layout-features.py JunicodeTwoBeta-Regular.ttf}}
   \label{fig:layout-features}
 \end{figure}

In 2018 a feature request was submitted to the \textsf{fntsample}
repository entitled \textit{Suggestion:\ enable printing glyphs not
assigned to a unicode
slot},\footnote{\tbsurl{github.com/eugmes/fntsample/issues/11}}
but there was no follow up. In 2021 a similar feature request was
made for
\textsf{unicodefonttable}.\footnote{\raggedright
\tbsurl{github.com/FrankMittelbach/fmitex-unicodefonttable/issues/2}} The
answer, in my view correct, was that this should be a
separate project.


We focus here on discussing the annotations in \textsf{ttx}'s \XML\ form
(but the
fork of \textsf{layout-features.py} may also be considered). How to
process this information further is another question outside the scope
of this note. One possible approach is to continue the work on the
\textsf{fntsample} fork.  Another possibility is to use \XSLT\ to convert
to \LaTeX{} (running under \XeTeX{}  or \LuaTeX); this is a
general recommendation of
David Carlisle, the author of
\textsf{xmltex}.\footnote{\tbsurl{tex.stackexchange.com/questions/562856}}


The Unicode standard is updated every year, so we need a way to handle
the update conveniently.  Conversion to \XML\ with Parafiński's parser,
after some minor improvements of the program, seems a satisfactory
solution.

In the Private Use Area, the updates to Medieval Unicode Font Initiative
recommendation, for example, don't have a stable specific form. The
data, e.g., as prepared for Parafi\'nski's program, have to be
updated by hand.


One way to extract the interesting information from the font which
seems to be worth consideration consists of using the \textsf{ttx} plain text
format of OpenType\slash TrueType fonts produced by the program of the
same name.\footnote{\tbsurl{https://github.com/fonttools/fonttools}; see also
\cite[p.~22]{haralambous07:_fonts_encod}.}

To make the output more human readable, by default \texttt{ttx} uses the
character names from the file \fname{UnicodeData.txt} belonging to the
Unicode Character Database. There is, however, an option to provide a
different file for the data. One occasion for this is a new version of
the standard which has not yet migrated to the relevant software
libraries. The second, more important for us, is to provide names of the
\acro{PUA} characters, including \acro{MUFI}, prepared already in the
appropriate format by Rebecca~G.
Bettencourt\footnote{\tbsurl{kreativekorp.com/charset/PUADATA/PUBLIC/MUFI}}
(updates are probably needed).

OpenType/TrueType fonts consist of several tables and subtables,
which \textsf{ttx} converts to \XML\ (in the examples
below, the formatting is slightly changed).
% formatting changed to fit narrow columns. Can be undone.
Variation
and tag sequences are represented in the same way as other
ligatures. For example, in \fname{NotoSans-Regular.ttf} the slashed
zero variation sequence (surprisingly few fonts support this variation
sequence), stored in the \texttt{GSUB} (Glyph Substitution) table, looks
like this:

\begin{verbatim}[\small]
<GSUB>
  <Version value="0x00010000"/>
  ...
  <LookupList>
    <!-- LookupCount=43 -->
    <Lookup index="2">
      ...
      <!-- SubTableCount=1 -->
      <LigatureSubst index="0" Format="1">
        <LigatureSet glyph="zero">
          <Ligature components="uniFE00" 
                    glyph="zero.slash"/>
        </LigatureSet>
      </LigatureSubst>
    </Lookup>
    ...
   </LookupList>
</GSUB>
\end{verbatim}

To discover what \texttt{uniFE00} definitively means, we consult
the \texttt{cmap} (Character to Glyph Index Mapping) table:

\begin{verbatim}[\small]
 <cmap>
  <tableVersion version="0"/>
  <cmap_format_4 platformID="0" 
                 platEncID="3" 
                 language="0">
    ...
      <map code="0xfe00" name="uniFE00"/>
           <!-- VARIATION SELECTOR-1 -->
  </cmap_format_4>
  ...
</cmap>
\end{verbatim}
The comments are provided by the \textsf{ttx} program.

As for \texttt{zero.slash}, we can use the auxiliary table
\texttt{GlyphOrder} produced by \textsf{ttx} to find the font slot
number of the character:

\begin{verbatim}[\small]
  <GlyphOrder>
    <!-- The 'id' attribute is only for humans; 
         it is ignored when parsed. -->
    ...
    <GlyphID id="2581" name="zero.slash"/>
    ..
   </GlyphOrder>
\end{verbatim}

The slot number can be used to typeset the character; in \XeTeX{} the
appropriate command is \verb|\XeTeXglyph|.\footnote{\raggedright This
was kindly pointed out to me by Ulrike Fischer on the \XeTeX\ mailing
list
(\tbsurl{tug.org/pipermail/xetex/2022-October/028105.html}).
\font\EdNoteFont = cmu10 at 1em
[\xEdNote{For Lua\TeX, some Lua code can achieve the same result; see
\tbsurl{https://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/120736}.]}}

Let's now consider another example, namely \textit{b~quad\-ra\-tum} from the
Junicode font mentioned above. The tag sequence is active only when stylistic set 10 is selected, so the ligature has to be embedded in the appropriate \texttt{FeatureElement}:

\begin{verbatim}[\small]
<GSUB>
  <Version value="0x00010000"/>
  ...
  <FeatureList>
    <!-- FeatureCount=155 -->
    ...
    <FeatureRecord index="140">
      <FeatureTag value="ss10"/>
      <!-- Character Entities 
           for Combining Marks -->
      <Feature>
        <FeatureParamsStylisticSet>
          <Version value="0"/>
          <UINameID value="256"/>  
                    <!-- Entities -->
        </FeatureParamsStylisticSet>
        <!-- LookupCount=3 -->
        ...
        <LookupListIndex index="2" 
                         dopiskivalue="71"/>
      </Feature>
    </FeatureRecord>
  ...
  </FeatureList>
  <LookupList>
    <!-- LookupCount=234 -->
    ...
    <Lookup index="71">
      <LookupType value="4"/>
      <LookupFlag value="16"/>
                 <!-- useMarkFilteringSet -->
      <!-- SubTableCount=1 -->
      <LigatureSubst index="0" Format="1">
        ...
        <LigatureSet glyph="b">
          <Ligature components="e.tag,n.tag" 
                    glyph="b.enlarged"/>
          <Ligature components="p.tag,l.tag" 
                    glyph="b.p02"/>
          <Ligature components="p.tag,s.tag" 
                    glyph="b.p01"/>
        </LigatureSet>
        ...
      </LigatureSubst>
      <MarkFilteringSet value="1"/>
    </Lookup>
  ...
  </LookupList>
</GSUB>
\end{verbatim}

In general the glyph selection can depend on a script, a language, and
user-selected features, which make the font structure quite
complicated. A program intended to extract all the information about a
font has to take everything into account.

\section{Final remark}
\label{sec:final-remarks}

I hope this note will provide inspiration to a reader or readers with
appropriate skills and in some future we will see a tool for
printing annotated font tables in a nice fashion.

